# Step 1: Creating the EC2


Navigate to AWS Console → EC2 → Launch Instance
Add a name for this EC2.
AMI = Amazon Linux 2023, Instance type = t3.micro, Key Pair= An existing pair you have or created a new one.
Network= The custom VPC you may already have, Private Subnet, Auto-Assign Public IP= Disabled.
Security Group= Create a new one.
User Data= Add a file that may already exist or paste the code into the box that appears.
The code as follows:
#!/bin/bash
dnf update -y
dnf install -y httpd

systemctl start httpd
systemctl enable httpd

echo "<h1>ALB Web Server</h1>" > /var/www/html/index.html
In this case, it downloads Apache and this will display the page as ALB Web Server.
Once completed, launch the EC2.


# Step 2: Launch the second EC2 Instance


Use the same details as above. Only have a different private subnet and create an additional web server.
Now you should have two instances.


# Step 3: Create a EC2 Security Group rule


Head to the EC2 Instance - Security Groups - The security group that was created.
Edit Inbound rules, and add HTTP.


# Step 4: ALB Security Group


Head to VPC - Security Groups - Create security group
Add a name to the group and the following inbound rules:
HTTP: Port 80, Source = Anywhere IPv4, 
Outbound: Leave as default settings (All traffic).
create security group.


# Step 5: Restrict the EC2 only to the ALB (Application Load Balancer).


Navigate back to Instances - Security Groups.
Go to the  first security group created, Edit inbound rules and remove the temporary HTTP placeholder.
Add a HTTP inbound rule with the Application Load Balancer Security Group attached.
This will ensure any traffic from the ALB points to the web servers that were created.


# Step 6: Target Groups

Navigate to Target Groups in Instances - Create target group.
Use the following for the properties:
Target type= Instances, Name the Target Group, Protocol= HTTP, Port = 80, IP Address= IPv4, VPC= Your created one.
Health Check: /, All other properties are left as default.
Click Next - Register Targets.
Select your Security Group.
Include as pending below, then click Create Target group.


# Step 7: Create the Application Load Balancer


Navigate to Load Balancers - Create - Choose Application Load Balancer.
Add the following custom properties:
Choose a suitable Name, Scheme= Internet Facing, IP= IPv4, 
Network Mapping= Choose your VPC, Both Private Subnets, and spread the ALB to two Availability Zones.
Security group created for the Application Load Balancer, Listene= HTTP:80, Forward to the TG that you had created in the last step.
Leave everything else as it is, Create load balancer.


# Step 8: Health Checks


Head to the target group you created on: Target Groups.
From here, check to see your target is showing as Healthy.
If unhealthy, check the following: 
Apache is running, User data completed successfully, EC2 instances have a route to the internet (via NAT Gateway if in private subnets) so they could install packages.
Security groups allow ALB → EC2 on port 80.


# Step 9: Tests

Head to Load Balancers and select your LB.
Copy the DNS name and paste it into your browser.


# Step 10: Confirmation

Verify EC2 is not Publicy Accessible due to no public IP, private subnates and only being able to accept HTTP from the Security Group created for the ALB.



